title: 16.0.3 iPhone 14 Pro Notification Bugs
text:
Summary:
Issue one: Notifications (namely badges) shown on my home screen aren‚Äôt reflective of what‚Äôs in the app. 

Issue two: I‚Äôm unable to modify my notification settings if I don‚Äôt choose ‚ÄúAllow Notifications‚Äù in the onboarding flow. 

Details:

Steps to recreate Issue one:
1. In the app, turn off all notification settings except messages
2. Read all messages (including new ‚Äúlikes‚Äù) 
3. Return to the Home Screen 

Expected result: no badge should be shown on the app icon
Actual result: a badge is showing on the app icon

Steps to recreate Issue 2:
1. Delete Tinder
2. Download the latest build from the App Store 
3. Go thru the onboarding flow
4. When Tinder asks if I want notifications, I say ‚ÄúDon‚Äôt Allow‚Äù
5. Finish the onboarding and close the app
6. Go to Settings > Notifications and look for Tinder 

Expected result: Tinder should be on the list in its alphabetical order to allow me to modify settings
Actual result: Tinder is not on the list at all

ALTERNATE Steps to recreate Issue 2:
1. Delete Tinder
2. Download the latest build from the App Store 
3. Go thru the onboarding flow
4. When Tinder asks if I want notifications, I say ‚ÄúALLOW‚Äù
5. Finish the onboarding and close the app
6. Go to Settings > Notifications and look for Tinder 

Expected result: Tinder should be on the list in its alphabetical order 
Actual result: Tinder *IS* on the list

title: Prepare to get Banned For No Reason
text:
The app is great, and I‚Äôve always had a good time on it. But out of nowhere, I tried to login and found out my account was banned. And when this happens, there‚Äôs no appeal process and they don‚Äôt give you ANY reason as to why it happened. The reason why I‚Äôm guessing I got banned was because I accidentally glitched out of the photo verification process and they just shut my account down. It seems I‚Äôm not the only one, too. 

Their support is also atrocious. Good luck actually talking to a human being. I tried submitting a request on their website, and got an automated response basically saying tough luck. They put a phone number on their website, but the line goes dead when you try to call. You can go on their support site on Twitter and you‚Äôll see just how terrible they are. They honestly don‚Äôt care about you, even if you pay them $89 + a year for their useless premium subscriptions.  

What‚Äôs also troubling is that people who ACTUALLY DESERVE to be banned are running rampant on that app! There‚Äôs bots, people being sexually harassed (pictures of that on twitter, and they had a generic ‚ÄúI‚Äôm sorry‚Äù response to it), and constant spam accounts. Even worse, I saw that trans people are being banned also for no reason! Additionally, if they ban you here, they‚Äôre highly likely to do the same on other apps their parent corporation is affiliated with (OkCupid, Hinge). 

In short, just try other apps. Once they ban you, you can never use it again.

title: Goodbye, Tinder. (And all dating apps)
text:
The time has come, boys. Tinder from 2016-2019 was unbelievable. Thank you, Tinder, for the great times. I wish this app never fell off, but I understand. So many subconscious standards from social media/Hollywood have made it almost impossible to find a mere date on Tinder. 

It‚Äôs not rocket science. It‚Äôs pretty simple why this phenomenon is occurring. First of all we are in the most feminist time in history. And I‚Äôm not saying that‚Äôs a bad thing. It just so happens to be that a good thing indirectly is affecting a large portion of young males disproportionately. I am not here to blame feminism on the decline of my romantic career, but rather simply stating that there is a noticeable increase in the standards to date a girl that you find attractive to even begin with. 

I get it, you want to have the Bearded 29-32 year old with a truck, property, and a high paying job. Or you want the surfer fem boy from UCLA, who has a sleek chiseled face like Channing Tatum. I get it. More power to you right? Overall, yeah I‚Äôm a little butt hurt that girls have raised their standards so high that most don‚Äôt even need dating apps cause their DMs are already filled to brim. 

After thinking some things through and making some key changes in my life, I have one suggestion to those on the same boat: work on yourselves. Forgot to add: the gym may not attract women but not going to the gym will definitely ensure that. HEAD UP KINGS.

title: Beware con artists, data harvesting, catfishing
text:
There are so many fake accounts. Any use of this app brings serious risk of exposure to data harvesting scams and catfishing. If you manage to avoid that, there is trolling and sexual harassment to navigate. If you get past that, you have the great mass of confused humanity to navigate. 
Tinder is little incentive to combat this: fake accounts, et cetera inflate subscriber numbers, app traffic, and therefore help to underpin the valuation of the company. 
Do yourself a favor. Go somewhere new, irl. Explore you interests, and take them a little further irl. See who you meet there. The social experience will serve you well.

title: If you are a male: DO NOT DOWNLOAD THIS APP
text:
For reference, I‚Äôm a good conversationalist, I have a decent job, I‚Äôm physically fit, have a healthy social life, and I live in a metropolitan area. 

I do not swipe right on every person I see, but rather take the time to look through profiles and be realistic. I also used to be a photographer, so my pictures were always well done. 

Unless you‚Äôre a total hunk/man candy, trust me when I say you‚Äôre wasting your time. Tinder profits from the misery of men who are either looking for something casual or a meaningful relationship. Even as a ‚Äúnormal‚Äù guy, you won‚Äôt find anything with a ‚Äúnormal‚Äù girl. It‚Äôs just not designed that way. 

Over the years, I‚Äôve probably had around 100 matches. Of those matches, minus people I know IRL and scammers, I have had exactly zero conversations. 

I‚Äôve gone through a million cycles of deleting and redownloading Tinder. Paid for boosts, tried tinder gold a few times, and the result is always the same. No real connection for either a relationship or a hookup or even a friend. Just scammers, girls who want attention/validation from guys they won‚Äôt pursue, and possibly people that you already knew. Let this be your wake up call. 

If you‚Äôre a normal guy, Tinder does not work. Try hinge if you‚Äôre that afraid of talking to be people in the real world; I‚Äôve heard some good things about it. But honestly, just be yourself, have a healthy social life, go outside, explore the universe, and you‚Äôll meet people along the way. Don‚Äôt let this dogwater app ruin your confidence. 

It goes without saying that I will never be downloading Tinder again. Keep your chin up, Tinder isn‚Äôt real. Life is though.

title: Yikes.
text:
Personally, I am very disappointed with Tinder.
I‚Äôve been using the app on and off for about a year when I‚Äôve been in and out of relationships, and I really enjoyed my experience. I met loads of awesome people on the app and while very few ever turned into anything in person, it was a nice distraction. A couple days ago, I opened the app to discover I was banned. Now, this came as a surprise to me, because I had done nothing wrong to be banned from the app. No explanation was provided in the app, and when I reached out to support, no explanation was provided because they ‚Äúdon‚Äôt provide explanations for why bans are issued and don‚Äôt offer appeals.‚Äù Yikes. This feels very targeted and personally I am very disappointed and disgusted with the way Tinder handles their banning process. At the very least - I deserve to know what rule I supposedly violated that led me to be banned from the app. To provide no explanation at all is just another example of Tinder having absolutely no regard for the safety of its users or caring about its users at all. Sincerely, and I mean GENUINELY disappointed in Tinder. Tinder - do better. You are taking advantage of your users and people are noticing.
-J.
